@node Refiling trashing and moving without confirmation
@section Refiling, trashing, and moving without confirmation

@findex mu4e-extras-headers-refile
@findex mu4e-extras-view-refile
@findex mu4e-extras-headers-trash
@findex mu4e-extras-view-trash
@findex mu4e-extras-headers-move
@findex mu4e-extras-view-move
@findex mu4e-extras-mark-execute-all-no-confirm
The standard @samp{mu4e} mark-and-execute workflow requires an explicit
confirmation step.  The commands in this section bypass that
confirmation, performing the action immediately on the message at point.

The commands @code{mu4e-extras-headers-refile} and @code{mu4e-extras-view-refile}
refile the message at point in headers mode and view mode respectively.
Similarly, @code{mu4e-extras-headers-trash} and @code{mu4e-extras-view-trash}
trash the message, while @code{mu4e-extras-headers-move} and
@code{mu4e-extras-view-move} prompt for a target folder and move the message
immediately.

The command @code{mu4e-extras-mark-execute-all-no-confirm} executes all
pending marks in the current buffer without asking for confirmation.

@node Marking as read and refiling
@section Marking as read and refiling

@findex mu4e-extras-headers-mark-read-and-refile
The command @code{mu4e-extras-headers-mark-read-and-refile} combines two
actions: it marks the message at point as read and refiles it.  The
message's ID is added to an internal queue so that its read status can
be re-applied after the next Gmail synchronization (@ref{Read status management}).

This command exists because Gmail's IMAP implementation sometimes resets
the read flag on refiled messages during synchronization.  By queuing
the message, the package ensures the flag is restored automatically.

@node Initializing and updating mail
@section Initializing and updating mail

@findex mu4e-extras-init
@findex mu4e-extras-update-all-mail-and-index
@findex mu4e-extras-check-all-mail
@findex mu4e-extras-reindex-db
The command @code{mu4e-extras-init} reinitializes the @samp{mu} database.  It
stops any running mail update, quits @samp{mu4e}, and then runs the @samp{muinit}
script asynchronously.  Use this when the database is corrupted or after
major configuration changes.

The command @code{mu4e-extras-update-all-mail-and-index} fetches all mail
including archives from all accounts, then indexes with @samp{mu}.  It runs
@samp{mbsync gmail-all} for the personal account and
@samp{gmail-maildir-sync pull --include-all} for the Epoch account in
parallel (the Epoch account uses the Gmail API instead of IMAP, since
the Epoch Google Workspace admin has disabled IMAP).  With a prefix
argument, it runs in the background; otherwise, it shows a progress
window.

Mail updates run from the current buffer's @code{default-directory} when that
directory still exists, and from the user's home directory otherwise.
This prevents @samp{mu4e}'s subprocess startup from failing when a manual or
timer-triggered update runs after the current worktree directory has
been deleted.

The command @code{mu4e-extras-check-all-mail} performs the same operation as
@code{mu4e-extras-update-all-mail-and-index} but always runs in the
background.  It is intended for periodic full syncs that can take longer.

The command @code{mu4e-extras-reindex-db} kills any running @samp{mu} process and
then runs @samp{mu index} to rebuild the index.

@node Composing messages
@section Composing messages

@findex mu4e-extras-compose-reply
@findex mu4e-extras-compose-new-externally
The command @code{mu4e-extras-compose-reply} initiates a reply to the message
at point.  If the sender is the current user, it calls
@code{mu4e-compose-supersede} to edit the sent message.  When there are
multiple recipients, the behavior depends on the @code{mu4e-extras-wide-reply}
user option (@ref{Reply behavior}).

The command @code{mu4e-extras-compose-new-externally} opens Gmail's compose
screen in a browser, bypassing @samp{mu4e} entirely.  It always opens in
the personal Chrome profile (@ref{Chrome profile selection}).

@node Gmail reactions
@section Gmail reactions

@findex mu4e-extras-react-to-message
The command @code{mu4e-extras-react-to-message} reacts to the email at point
with a Gmail emoji reaction.  It prompts the user to select an emoji
from @code{mu4e-extras-reaction-emojis} (@ref{Reaction emojis}), then constructs a
MIME message per Google's email reaction format specification (using a
@samp{text/vnd.google.email-reaction+json} part) and sends it to the
original sender.

The command automatically determines the sending account by checking
which of the user's email addresses appears in the message's To or Cc
fields.  Epoch messages are sent via the Gmail API (through
@samp{gmail-maildir-sync send}); personal and Tlon messages are sent via
SMTP@.

@node Viewing messages in Gmail
@section Viewing messages in Gmail

@findex mu4e-extras-open-gmail
@findex mu4e-extras-view-in-gmail
@findex mu4e-extras-gmail-base
@findex mu4e-extras-gmail-message-id
@findex mu4e-extras-gmail-thread-id
@vindex mu4e-extras-gmail-sync-state-db
The function @code{mu4e-extras-gmail-base} returns the base Gmail URL
(@samp{https://mail.google.com/mail/u/0/}).  It uses account index 0
because Chrome profile selection (@ref{Chrome profile selection}) already
routes to the correct account, making email-based account resolution
in the URL unnecessary.

The command @code{mu4e-extras-open-gmail} opens the Gmail inbox in a browser.
When called from a message buffer, it detects the message's account and
opens the URL in the corresponding Chrome profile (@ref{Chrome profile selection, , Chrome profile
selection}).  When no message is at point, it defaults to the personal
profile.

The command @code{mu4e-extras-view-in-gmail} opens the message at point in
Gmail.  For messages synced via @code{gmail-maildir-sync} (Epoch account), it
reads the @samp{X-Gmail-Message-Id} header from the message file, looks up
the corresponding thread ID from the @code{gmail-maildir-sync} SQLite state
database (@code{mu4e-extras-gmail-sync-state-db}), and opens the thread
directly using a @code{#all/<thread-id>} URL@.  For other messages (personal
account), it falls back to searching by RFC 822 message ID@.  The URL is
opened in the Chrome profile matching the message's account
(@ref{Chrome profile selection}).  This is useful when you need to perform an
action that @samp{mu4e} does not support, such as viewing the full HTML
rendering or accessing Gmail-specific features.

@node Message file operations
@section Message file operations

@findex mu4e-extras-copy-message-path
@findex mu4e-extras-open-message-file
The command @code{mu4e-extras-copy-message-path} copies the filesystem path
of the current message to the kill ring.  This is useful when you need
to pass the path to an external tool or paste it into a shell command.
It uses @code{mu4e-extras-get-message-file} internally
(@ref{Message file access}).

The command @code{mu4e-extras-open-message-file} opens the file on disk that
stores the current message.  It uses @code{dired-jump} to display the file
in its parent directory in Dired mode.  This is useful for inspecting
raw message files or managing mail storage.

@node Org capture integration
@section Org capture integration

@findex mu4e-extras-view-org-capture
The command @code{mu4e-extras-view-org-capture} captures the message at point
using @samp{org-capture}.  By default it uses the template key @samp{"e"}, but if
the message body contains the string @samp{[org-capture key: KEY]}, it uses
KEY instead.  This allows automated email workflows to specify which
capture template should process the message.

Without a prefix argument, the message is refiled after capture (via
@code{mu4e-extras-view-refile}).  With a prefix argument, the message is
captured but not refiled, leaving it in the inbox.

This command works in both @code{mu4e-view-mode} and @code{mu4e-headers-mode}.

@node Copying information
@section Copying information

@findex mu4e-extras-copy-number-in-title
The command @code{mu4e-extras-copy-number-in-title} extracts a numeric value
from the subject line of the message at point and copies it to the kill
ring.  This is useful for quickly capturing amounts from transactional
emails (e.g., invoices, receipts) without opening the message.

